entries.meaning: (agriculture, fishery) (of nuts, eggs, shellfish) Not removed from the shell.
examples: Live inshell scallops are preferable to frozen scallop meats.

entries.meaning: (agriculture, fishery) A product (nut, shellfish) that has not been removed from its shell.
examples: Inshells are shipped in 50-pound sacks, while shelled walnut pieces are shipped in 25-pound bags'

verbs.description: inshell (third-person singular simple present inshells, present participle inshelling, simple past and past participle inshelled)

entries.meaning: (literary, rare) To enclose in a shell.
examples: […]  of all men that I have ever known, no one was more reluctant to creep out of the modesty in which he had inshelled himself, than the man whom I cannot even yet think no more, feeling towards his memory as if he were still waiting for something not received.
